{
  "doc_id": "29519",
  "text": "Foams consist of a dispersion of a gaseous phase in a continuous aqueous or solid phase [CITATION_1] . A pure liquid does not produce foam, but the decrease in surface tension by the addition of surfactants allows foam production. Foam is generally unstable both thermodynamically and kinetically, especially under formation condition. The two most important foaming properties of a liquid are how easily foam is formed (foamability) and how easily the foam collapses (stability) [CITATION_2] . In most foamy foods pectins help in the formation and stabilization of the dispersed gaseous phase.",
